#Do a little data scrubbing
meps.sub$PID <- as.factor(meps.sub$PID)
meps.sub$SEX <- as.factor(meps.sub$SEX)
meps.sub$REGION14 <- as.factor(meps.sub$REGION14)

Create a split box plot.

For this I will select age (AGE14X) as numeric variable and region (REGION14) as categorical variable.

## 
##    -1     1     2     3     4 
##   209  5292  6299 13135  9940

Doesn’t seem to be any material differences between regions. Except for region -1, which seems to indicate missing values. This would seem to indicate some link between missing region and missing age. There is likely an admininstrative link, e.g. they come from the same survey/agency.

View as stacked and split histograms.

#CHUNK 3
library(gridExtra) #for gridArrange

## Stacked histogram
p1 <- ggplot(data = meps.sub, aes(AGE14X, fill=REGION14, ..density..)) +
       geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, alpha = 0.5)

## Split histogram
p2 <- ggplot(data = meps.sub, aes(AGE14X, fill=REGION14, ..density..)) +
       geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, alpha = 0.5, position = "dodge")
grid.arrange(p1,p2,ncol=1)

Region -1 is distorting the viz. Since we’ve already surmised that it is missing data, let’s just leave out and look again.

#CHUNK 3b
library(gridExtra) #for gridArrange

## Stacked histogram
p1 <- ggplot(data = meps.sub[meps.sub$REGION14 != '-1',], aes(AGE14X, fill=REGION14, ..density..)) +
       geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, alpha = 0.5)

## Split histogram
p2 <- ggplot(data = meps.sub[meps.sub$REGION14 != '-1',], aes(AGE14X, fill=REGION14, ..density..)) +
       geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, alpha = 0.5, position = "dodge")
grid.arrange(p1,p2,ncol=1)

There appears to be a weird ‘jagged’ edge at age 0. Maybe some of those ‘missing’ values are actually age 0? Will leave that for an exploration at another time.

Build a stacked bar chart of region vs SEX.
p1 <- ggplot(data = meps.sub, aes(x = REGION14, fill = SEX)) +
        geom_bar(stat = "count", alpha = 0.5)
p2 <- ggplot(data = meps.sub, aes(x = REGION14, fill = SEX)) +
        geom_bar(stat = "count", alpha = 0.5, position = "dodge")
grid.arrange(p1,p2,ncol=2)

Looks that consistent across regions there are more females (2) than males (1).

Run a heat map. For this we will explore age vs family income (FAMINC14)

Seems to follow intution; income increases with age. Note one flaw could be that it is FAMILY income, so we could be double counting since each observation is a person. Seems slightly bimodal.

Scatterplot - Age vs Family Income

Instead of a heat map let’s try a scatter plot. Color by region.

#scatterplot
pid <- ggplot(data = meps.sub, aes(x = AGE14X, y = FAMINC14, color = REGION14)) +
        geom_point(alpha = 0.2)
pid

#Save a png
ggsave("ex4_2_9_plot1.png")

There doesn’t appear to be anything telling region-wise, aside from region ‘-1’ again; note the red markers all along the Y-axis. Also that slight hint of bimodal-ness shows.

Total Health care expenditures vs amount paid by private insurance.

This is a bit of a trivial example, but seems to really confirm our intuition. If you have insurance, then it likely pays for all of the expenditure. This can be seen in the 45 degree ‘V’ shape. The 45% line indicates where it’s all/most paid by private insurance, where the line parallel to the x-axis indicates where none/little is paid by private insurance.

pie <- ggplot(data = meps.sub, aes(x = TOTEXP14, y = TOTPRV14, color = REGION14)) +
        geom_point(alpha = 0.2)
pie
